### File Structure
```
EventPlanning/
│
├── app.py
├── templates/
│   ├── dashboard.html
│   ├── events_listing.html
│   ├── event_details.html
│   ├── ticket_booking.html
│   ├── participants_management.html
│   ├── venues.html
│   ├── event_schedules.html
│   └── bookings_summary.html
│
├── static/
│   ├── css/
│   │   └── styles.css
│   ├── js/
│   │   └── scripts.js
│   └── images/
│       └── (event and venue images if any)
│
└── data/
    ├── events.txt
    ├── venues.txt
    ├── tickets.txt
    ├── bookings.txt
    ├── participants.txt
    └── schedules.txt
```

### File Descriptions
```
1. app.py
   - The main backend Python file implementing the web application using a framework like Flask.
   - Handles routing for all eight pages (Dashboard, Events Listing, Event Details, Ticket Booking, Participants Management, Venues, Event Schedules, Bookings Summary).
   - Implements logic for reading from and writing to local text files in the 'data' directory.
   - Manages data parsing, filtering, searching, and booking operations.
   - Since the application is not very complex, all backend logic is consolidated here for maintainability.

2. templates/
   - Contains HTML template files for each page, following the page design and element IDs specified.
   - Each HTML file corresponds to one of the eight pages, structured with the required elements and IDs.
   - Templates will be rendered by app.py with dynamic data injected.

3. static/
   - Contains static assets such as CSS stylesheets, JavaScript files, and images.
   - css/styles.css: Styles for consistent UI design across pages.
   - js/scripts.js: Client-side scripts for interactivity, e.g., search filtering, button actions.
   - images/: Optional folder for event and venue images if needed.

4. data/
   - Stores all application data in text files as specified.
   - events.txt, venues.txt, tickets.txt, bookings.txt, participants.txt, schedules.txt contain the respective data in the defined pipe-separated format.
   - The backend reads from and writes to these files to persist application state.

This structure cleanly separates backend logic, frontend templates, static resources, and data storage, aligning with the project requirements and enabling straightforward development and maintenance.
```
